did.unittitle: Special Collections Department, Gelman Library records
did.abstract: Special materials was always a part of the University's library collections; however, it was not until 1973, and the opening of the Gelman Library, that the University's special materials were housed together in proper storage and service areas. Materials in this collection include publications on the Elliott School of International Affairs, the symposium at GW on George Gamow, Baptist Church materials, bibliographies of faculty publications. and other exhibit materials including programs, postcards, labels, and videocasettes.

bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Special materials was always a part of the University's library collections; however, it was not until 1973, and the opening of the Gelman Library, that the University's special materials were housed together in proper storage and service areas. Before the construction of the Lisner Library in 1939, many of the collections' rare books and materials were stored in Columbian House. After the completion of Lisner, they were transferred to a large vault on the fourth floor of the new library. When the Special Collections Division was set up in the Gelman Library, many rare items, long ago packed away, were brought to light. The Special Collections Department began in 1968 as part of the Lisner Library.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Materials in this collection include signage for exhibits and events, gifts, proposed and rejected, statistics, correspondence, theses, projects, biographical information, notes, faculty authors' information, 143 slides on the history of GW libraries, 37 slides on the history of cheerleading, 33 slides on the history of the Elliott School of International Affairs, photographs, posters, 25th anniversaries of the Gelman Library, photographs and prints used in the World War II exhibit, oral history transcripts, photocopies of books, videotapes from the April 12, 1996 Symposium at GW on George Gamow, Baptist Church materials, bibliographies of faculty publications, accession records, and other exhibit materials including programs, postcards, labels, and videocasettes. One of the exhibits was to commemorate the 35th anniversary of the March on Washington and another exhibit was titled "The President's Physician: The Life And Legacy Of Dr. Janet G. Travell." The collection covers the years 1819 to 2014.
Formerly RG 17.3.4

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized in 20 series: Proposed gifts; Statistics, correspondence, exhibit materials; Faculty Author program; Acquisitions; Exhibit files, Exhibit; Slides; Public programming; Photographs and posters; Faculty publications, Photographs, George Washington University; Transcripts, papers, correspondence; Exhibits and collections; Janet G. Travell exhibit; March on Washington exhibit, and Exhibits, Events, UA Records Management Program, and Diversity Fellowship student projects collection; Accession Records

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series 5 contains material accumulated throughout the preparation and execution of exhibits in Gelman Library. This material includes notes, corresondence, plans and diagrams of exhibit layouts, research material, photocopies of displayed material, photographs, negatives, captions, catalogs, programs, brochures, loan agreements, and guest books. The material dates between 1935 and 2003, with the bulk between 1973 and 2003.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series consists of of photographs, photocopy reproductions, a videotape, and labels. The exhibit titled "The President's Physician: The Life And Legacy Of Dr. Janet G. Travell" was displayed in Gelman Library's Special Collections Department from January-August 2003. The videotape was of an exhibit program with Henry Fishman, Lawrence Funt, Robert Gerwin, and Nancy Shaw sharing memories of Dr. Travell. The reproductions included an article from Texas Heart Institute Journal titled "Janet G. Travell, MD: A Daughter's Recollection."

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The inaugural cohort of University Archives Diversity Research Fellowsarcia, Tasha Dorsey and Dominic Amaralthrough the University Archives at the GW Libraries to dig up these unsung stories, examining the lives of the nonacademic staff, women, international students and veterans who have contributed to GW's history.

The program was developed by the University Archivist to bring the campus community closer to the history of the university. This project gives students the opportunity to assist the work of the University Archives to preserve the fascinating legacy of GW.

The fellows were selected by a committee of faculty and staff from the Special Collections Research Center at the beginning of the academic year and awarded a stipend. Funding for the program was supplied through an Innovations in Diversity and Inclusion grant from the Office of Diversity and Inclusion.
The plan is for the diversity fellowship program to cotinue.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Please cite unpublished materials in the following way:
Please provide the title and date of item, catalog number (if applicable it will be found written on the folder), name of the collection, name of the repository, and location of the repository.

Example: James Oglethorpe to the Trustees, 13 January 1876, RG0001 Series 1, Box 4, Folder 3. Records of the Board of Trustees, Special Collections Research Center, Gelman Library, The George Washington University, Washington, D.C.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains the digital files of the Fellows. These include formats such as Powerpoint of the final presentations, Word documents of the research conducted and analysis of data, and mp3 files of interviews. These documents were all created in 2014.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged alphabeically by last name of Fellow.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: A veteran, Mr. Dominic Amaral, B.A. '14, applied for the program at the urging of Michael Ruybal, associate director of the Office of Military and Veteran Student Services. Mr. Amaral scoured 50 years of veterans' history at GW, beginning with 1900. He was fascinated by the university's flexibility at the onset of World War I, when GW developed courses focused on firearms, camouflage and ship hull engineering to better educate the changing student body. By the end of WWI there were 1,200 veterans out of 3,200 students, he said.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Tasha Dorsey, a graduate student in the Columbian College of Arts and Sciences' clinical psychology program, based her project friendships she formed with the cafeteria staff an undergraduate at the United States Naval Academy. These relationships inspired her interest in researching the lives of staff members at GW.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: For rising senior Isabel Maria Garcia, a native of Ecuador, the project was personal. Garcia studied the emergence of international students at GW. Garcia said that the development of the English as a Foreign Language program, founded in the 1970s to serve international students, was a turning point for the international community on campus. By the mid-1970s there were 1,229 foreign students from 101 countries attending GW.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Eden Orelove conducted an in-depth study of women at GW and found that the Columbian Women organization has been a champion for female students for 125 years. She said that researching the place of women at GW in history was an important experience, from discovering the stories of alumni pioneers such as Antarctic explorer Jackie Ronne and aviator Jacqueline Cochran to learning about the Columbian Women's contribution to purchase a gram of radium for scientist Marie Curie.
